04647nam a22007935i 9780812293081DE-B159720180725125623.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||180725s2016    pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122930817 a10.9783/97808122930812doi  a(DE-B1597)487996  a(OCoLC)961065077  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA14aBS136b.K45 2016eb 7aLIT0110002bisacsh 7aREL0060802bisacsh04a220.5/2012231 aKelly, Henry Ansgar, eauthor.14aThe Middle English Bible :bA Reassessment /cHenry Ansgar Kelly. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Middle Ages Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- tChapter 1. A History of Judgments on the Middle English Bible -- tChapter 2. Five and Twenty Books as ''Official'' Prologue, or Not -- tChapter 3. The Bible at Oxford -- tChapter 4. Oxford Doctors, Archbishop Arundel, and Dives and Pauper on the Advisability of Scripture in English -- tChapter 5. The Provincial Constitutions of 1407 -- tChapter 6. Treatment of the English Bible in the Fifteenth Century -- tChapter 7. The End of the Story: Richard Hunne and Thomas More -- tConclusion -- tAppendices -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex  aIn the last quarter of the fourteenth century, the complete Old and New Testaments were translated from Latin into English, first very literally, and then revised into a more fluent, less Latinate style. This outstanding achievement, the Middle English Bible, is known by most modern scholars as the "Wycliffite" or "Lollard" Bible, attributing it to followers of the heretic John Wyclif. Prevailing scholarly opinion also holds that this Bible was condemned and banned by the archbishop of Canterbury, Thomas Arundel, at the Council of Oxford in 1407, even though it continued to be copied at a great rate. Indeed, Henry Ansgar Kelly notes, it was the most popular work in English of the Middle Ages and was frequently consulted for help in understanding Scripture readings at Sunday Mass.In The Middle English Bible: A Reassessment, Kelly finds the bases for the Wycliffite origins of the Middle English Bible to be mostly illusory. While there were attempts by the Lollard movement to appropriate or coopt it after the fact, the translation project, which appears to have originated at the University of Oxford, was wholly orthodox. Further, the 1407 Council did not ban translations but instead mandated that they be approved by a local bishop. It was only in the early sixteenth century, in the years before the Reformation, that English translations of the Bible would be banned.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Jul 2018) 4aLiterature. 4aMedieval and Renaissance Studies. 4aReligion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package 2017z978311055030608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook package 2017-2019z978311065989408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniv.of Pennsylvania Press eBook-Package 2017-2018z978311065747040uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/9780812293081423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812293081.jpg  a978-3-11-055030-6  Penn Press eBook Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-065747-0  Univ.of Pennsylvania Press eBook-Package 2017-2018  a978-3-11-065989-4  Penn Press eBook package 2017-2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA10PENN  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG